1
00:00:02,480 --> 00:00:12,380
E questo è tutto, ma non dimenticare Mario e mantenere il cuore.

2
00:00:15,880 --> 00:00:26,080
Come vedremo in dettaglio nell'introduzione, la vostra contribuzione è già più ricca e generosa.

3
00:00:28,320 --> 00:00:31,100
Tieni duro.

4
00:00:33,720 --> 00:00:49,200
And don't give up, resisti to the temptation we all experience with aging of saying, sono stanco e ho già dato.

5
00:00:58,300 --> 00:01:09,500
I invite now Professor Giuliano Amato to offer us a few words he might like to offer.

6
00:01:10,880 --> 00:01:15,500
Professor Amato, Minister Amato, you have the floor.

7
00:01:15,500 --> 00:01:21,340
Thank you. I didn't even expect to speak this morning.

8
00:01:23,220 --> 00:01:29,220
Non funziona? No, forse va.

9
00:01:31,680 --> 00:01:39,820
I was saying I didn't even expect to speak this morning, also because I have such a huge cold that speaking is difficult.

10
00:01:39,820 --> 00:01:51,060
But having said so, I'm here for the simple reason that Mario is now 70, I will be 70 next year,

11
00:01:51,700 --> 00:01:59,620
and we have been friends and working together every once in a while for most of our lives,

12
00:02:00,000 --> 00:02:03,900
which is quite a long time at this stage of our lives.

13
00:02:04,900 --> 00:02:13,880
Well, of course, Mario's life is, I was defining it in these words a few minutes ago, is really extravagant,

14
00:02:14,200 --> 00:02:21,020
because if you think of a young man going to Poland during the communist regime,

15
00:02:21,640 --> 00:02:29,900
working on the communist economy under teachers that were special teachers at the time,

16
00:02:29,900 --> 00:02:40,900
I remember, I myself, the first booklet by Oscar Lange translated into Italian is still in my personal bookshelves.

17
00:02:43,400 --> 00:02:55,240
But, I mean, at the time, the 60s, you could not expect the same man to be back in Poland more than 30 years later

18
00:02:55,240 --> 00:03:04,080
as an advisor to the finance minister of the time and working together for that economy

19
00:03:04,080 --> 00:03:12,480
just to go out of the communist patterns and reach the level of a market economy.

20
00:03:13,200 --> 00:03:15,260
And this is what he did.

21
00:03:17,140 --> 00:03:22,960
My personal reflection on this is that it makes sense.

22
00:03:22,960 --> 00:03:30,960
If you know Mario, what he has written, what he was looking for also in the 60s,

23
00:03:32,180 --> 00:03:40,860
I think that the finance minister of the post-communist Poland picked the right advisor,

24
00:03:41,360 --> 00:03:49,700
picked the right advisor, because Mario was not looking for the celebration of the communist economies of the time.

25
00:03:49,700 --> 00:03:57,100
He was looking for something impossible, at least it turned out impossible, the reform from inside.

26
00:03:57,920 --> 00:04:04,080
Several of us were thinking at the time that the reform from inside was feasible,

27
00:04:04,320 --> 00:04:12,930
but certainly looking for that, the relationship between the role of the state and market incentives

28
00:04:12,930 --> 00:04:25,330
was something that he could master much more than others who advised post-communist economies in transition,

29
00:04:26,290 --> 00:04:30,690
not mindful of essential aspects of the transition.

30
00:04:31,050 --> 00:04:33,810
And this is Mario's advantage.

31
00:04:35,490 --> 00:04:38,270
Privatizing without liberalizing.

32
00:04:38,270 --> 00:04:43,330
I remember that when he was in Poland the second time,

33
00:04:43,870 --> 00:04:49,650
I was head of the Italian Antitrust Authority and we were working with our Polish colleagues.

34
00:04:50,370 --> 00:04:58,430
And it was so clear to them and to me and to others how important it was going beyond privatization,

35
00:04:59,550 --> 00:05:02,530
creating the framework of a competitive economy,

36
00:05:02,530 --> 00:05:17,550
how important it was to rebuild the state and therefore to have not the destruction of the state,

37
00:05:18,270 --> 00:05:29,270
but a market-oriented public administration which is something that is still missing in some of the economies

38
00:05:29,270 --> 00:05:34,290
that we have in our Eastern Europe.

39
00:05:36,290 --> 00:05:48,130
The second reason for me to, let's say, sympathize with Mario's work is what economists call the economics of participation.

40
00:05:49,230 --> 00:05:57,550
In the late 70s I was heading the Institute of Research of the Main Italian Trade Union, CGL,

41
00:05:57,550 --> 00:06:02,550
at the time in a sort of joint venture with Bruno Trentin.

42
00:06:03,830 --> 00:06:11,910
Mario was around somehow and we were looking for new patterns of participation.

43
00:06:12,230 --> 00:06:17,470
We invented Bruno and I, the piano d'impresa, the enterprise plan,

44
00:06:17,930 --> 00:06:21,770
but there were other things, investment funds, etc.

45
00:06:21,770 --> 00:06:32,570
And Mario again, so eager to find out something that could work, everybody knows in Europe,

46
00:06:32,670 --> 00:06:49,730
how was the name of Pepper? Pepper was participation, promotion of employees, participation to profits and enterprise results.

47
00:06:49,730 --> 00:06:50,250
Pepper.

48
00:06:53,790 --> 00:06:56,070
The acronym was invented by Mario.

49
00:06:57,090 --> 00:07:08,590
So you see we have here his minister in Poland and you see the European head that invented this Pepper, great.

50
00:07:10,290 --> 00:07:18,250
Well, nowadays again this has remained a topic that needs the solution that we haven't found.

51
00:07:18,250 --> 00:07:21,970
In a time when, let's say, the share of...

